properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of snow expected for the latter half of this week. Locations: the mid Labrador coast from Rigolet to Makkovik. Time span: beginning late in the day on Wednesday and lasting into the weekend. Remarks: Snow will develop in the Rigolet area Wednesday afternoon before spreading to Postville-Makkovik area Wednesday night. Snow is expected to persist through Thursday and likely Friday as well, with significant accumulations possible. At this time, it looks as if conditions will begin to improve for most areas by Saturday but accumulating snow is possible through the remainder of the weekend. Further details will be provided in subsequent messages, as it is too soon to accurately forecast amounts and duration of precipitation due to uncertainty. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of mixed winter weather expected for the latter half of this week. Locations: Southeastern Labrador. Total rainfall through Wednesday night: 10 to 20 mm along the coast south of Black Tickle. Total snow and ice pellets through Wednesday night: 10 to 20 cm in the Cartwright and Eagle River areas. Time span: beginning overnight tonight and lasting into the weekend. Remarks: Snow and ice pellets will develop over southeastern Labrador late overnight tonight and will quickly change to rain Wednesday morning along the coast south of Black Tickle. A freezing rain warning has been issued from Norman Bay to L'Anse-au-Clair, including the Trans-Labrador Highway from Cartwright Junction. For the Cartwright and Eagle River areas, precipitation will fall primarily as a mix of snow and ice pellets Wednesday and Wednesday night. Freezing rain is also expected to mix with the snow and ice pellets Wednesday afternoon and evening. Conditions should improve slightly during the day on Thursday before another round of significant snowfall is anticipated for Thursday night into Friday. A break from the unsettled weather should begin by Saturday. Further details will be provided in subsequent forecasts, as it is too soon to accurately forecast amounts and duration of precipitation due to uncertainty. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
